latestReviews.body:
This works but it's really inefficient. It seems to take around 10 seconds to load a 15 minute song. However, [GDScriptAudioImport](https://github.com/Gianclgar/GDScriptAudioImport) seems like it would be way slower but it's faster (only ~5 seconds for the same song).

Edit: Did some more exhaustive tests.

```py
var old_start := OS.get_ticks_usec()
var _old_stream = GDScriptAudioImport.loadfile("res://copyrighted_song.wav")
var old_end := OS.get_ticks_usec()
print("Old: %dµs" % (old_end - old_start))

var new_start := OS.get_ticks_usec()
var new_stream := AudioStreamSample.new()
var err = new_stream.load("res://copyrighted_song.wav")
assert(err == OK)
var new_end := OS.get_ticks_usec()
print("New: %dµs" % (new_end - new_start))
```

Here is a two minute song:
```
Old: 687859µs
New: 1678019µs
```

And here is the test project. You'll need to supply your own copyrighted song.
[Test.zip](https://github.com/godotengine/godot/files/6407914/Test.zip)

Actually, this is also going to break if ``force_srgb`` is used or ``use_vertex_colors`` is enabled.

Probably what you should do is add something like the following at line 1003:
```
if (particles_anim_blend) {
    albedo_tex = mix(albedo_tex, texture(texture_albedo, particles_anim_next_frame_uv_coord), particles_anim_next_frame_mix);
}
```

This would allow you to delete the two conditions when assigned ALBEDO and ALPHA and would allow it to automatically use SRGB and COLOR as appropriate.

